questions.question:
Consider the following C functions.

int fun1(int n) {
    static int i = 0;
    if (n > 0) {
        ++i;
        fun1(n-1);
    }
    return (i);
}

int fun2(int n) {
    static int i = 0;
    if (n > 0) {
        i = i + fun1(n);
        fun2(n-1);
    }
    return (i);
}

The return value of fun2(5) is _________.

#include <stdio.h>
int foo(int S[], int size) {
    if (size == 0) return 0;
    if (size == 1) return 1;
    if (S[0] != S[1]) return 1 + foo(S+1, size-1);
    return foo(S+1, size-1);
}
int main() {
    int A[] = {0, 1, 2, 2, 2, 0, 0, 1, 1};
    printf("%d", foo(A, 9));
    return 0;
}

The value printed by the given C program is _________ (Answer in integer).

A. 4
B. 5
C. 6
D. 8

The function f is defined as follows:

int f(int n) {
    if (n <= 1) return 1;
    else if (n % 2 == 0) return f(n/2);
    else return f(3*n - 1);
}

Assuming that arbitrarily large integers can be passed as a parameter to the function, consider the following statements:

i.   The function f terminates for finitely many different values of n >= 2.
ii.  The function f terminates for infinitely many different values of n >= 2.
iii. The function f does not terminate for finitely many different values of n >= 2.
iv.  The function f does not terminate for infinitely many different values of n >= 2.

Which one of the following options is true of the above?

A. i and ii
B. i and iii
C. ii and iii
D. ii and iv
